[[File:Hash fossil.JPG|thumb|245px|A fossil hash]] Hash fossils are not actually one [[fossil]], they are many fossils in the same [[Rock (geology)|rock]]. The term hash fossil describes the fossil formed when all the [[organic material]] in an environment falls to the ocean floor and fossilizes, hence the name "[[wikt:hash|hash]]". When you look at a hash fossil, you actually are looking at a piece of ancient [[seabed]]. In hash fossils you can usually find the pieces of [[coral]]s, [[crinoid]]s, [[bryzoan]]s, and [[brachiopod]]s. Also you can rarely find a piece of a [[trilobite]]. Hash fossils are very common, and are most easily found in limestone.
