'''Lúcia Mendonça Previato''' (born 1949) is a [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] biologist. She was awarded the [[L'Oréal-UNESCO Awards for Women in Science]] in 2004 for her research into preventing [[Chagas disease]].
==Biography== Lúcia Mendonça Previato was born in 1949. She is married to Jose Osvaldo Previato and has two children, Anna and Peter. She graduated from St. Ursula University and earned her Doctorate at the [[Federal University of Rio de Janeiro]] in Microbiology and Immunology.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://glycob.oxfordjournals.org/content/14/6/15G.full | title=Glycobiologist Lucia Mendonça-Previato Receives Prestigious UNESCO-L'OREAL Award for Women in Science | publisher=Glycobiology | accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.org.br/~lmpreviato | title=Lucia Mendonça Previato | publisher=Brazilian Academy of Sciences | accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> She is also a recipient of the [[TWAS Prize]] in Biology.<ref name="Prizes and Awards">{{Cite web |url=http://twas.org/opportunities/prizes-and-awards |title=Prizes and Awards |date=2016 |publisher=The World Academy of Sciences}}</ref>
